\begin_layout Section
Fire weather
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary focus of this investigation is fire weather.
 Therefore, this section will introduce some important ideas to understand
 this topic.
 The fire weather background comprises three aspects.
 First, it explains which meteorological variables contribute to fire conditions.
 Additionally, it explains how they exert their influence and.
 This section also describes how mathematical models represent the effect
 of fire weather variables on bushfires.
 It includes a description of the Australian Forest Fire Danger Index (FFDI)
 to explain the quantification of fire weather.
 Finally, the relationship between heatwaves and fire weather is also described.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fire weather variables 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Fire-weather-variables"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fire weather is analyzed through variables such as wind, precipitation,
 air temperature, and relative humidity.
 The behaviour of this meteorological variables influences every aspect
 of bushfires, including their ignition, spread and intensity.
 Bushfires start if high temperatures, low levels of relative humidity and
 precipitation have dried vegetation to a flammable point.
 Winds also contribute in the ignition of bushfires by taking moisture content
 out of the vegetation and providing oxygen for combustion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bradstock2012"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, atmospheric instability favours the occurence of thunderstorms;
 which are a natural ignition source of bushfires 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BureauofMeteorology2008"

\end_inset

.
 The spread of bushfires is controlled by winds, which propagate them and
 also can change their flank 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BureauofMeteorology2008"

\end_inset

.
 Atmospheric instability also contributes to the spread of these events
 because it produces spotting (spotfires).
 The intensity of bushfires is determined by the flammability and distribution
 of vegetation; which are controlled by precipitation in seasonal time scales
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bradstock2012"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effect of fire weather variables on bushfires has been described in
 several mathematical models.
 These models represent the ignition, spread or intensity of bushfires.
 Modelling efforts focus on one of these aspects or a combination of them.
 For example, the Forest Fire Danger Index (FFDI) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "McArthur1966,McArthur1967"

\end_inset

 quantifies danger based on vegetation drying.
 Therefore, this index targets ignition.
 On the other hand, the effect of atmospheric instability in producing spotting
 is the basis of the Haines Index 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haines"

\end_inset

.
 This index focuses on spread and intensity.
 The Canadian Forest Fire Weather System 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VanWagner1974"

\end_inset

 models the three aspects.
 In most cases, fire weather modelling efforts require a calibration process.
 The calibrations account for local conditions such as the type of vegetation
 and topography.
 This investigation uses the FFDI to explore fire weather in the Southern
 Hemisphere because of its calibration criteria.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Forest Fire Danger Index
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Australian fire authorities use the Forest Fire Danger Index (FFDI) for
 risk management 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Luke1978"

\end_inset

.
 The index was originally formulated by Alan Grant McArthur
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "McArthur1966,McArthur1967"

\end_inset

.
 Initially, operators used mechanical meters to calculate the index 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Luke1978"

\end_inset

.
 A set of carboard wheels comprised these devices.
 The meters facilitated the introduction—dialling—of weather data to calculated
 the index.
 The FFDI was later formulated as equations by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Noble1980"

\end_inset

.
 The equation that represents the index is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
FFDI=2e^{(-0.45+0.987ln(DF)-0.0345RH+0.0338T+0.0234v)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
T: Air temperature (
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

C).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
v: Wind speed (Km/h).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
RH: Relative humidity (%).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DF: Drought factor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The design of the index requires that its computation takes maximum temperature
 values.
 This variable usually peaks in the afternoon 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lucas2010"

\end_inset

.
 The index also requieres the computation of a drought factor.
 This factor represents the effect of precipitation on fueld loads drying.
 
\end_layout

