\begin_layout Subsection
Heatwaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no universal definition for heatwaves 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nairn2013,Perkins2012"

\end_inset

.
 Most definitions characterize them as consecutive days with abnormally
 high temperatures 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nairn2013"

\end_inset

.
 More technical definitions adopt thresholds or percentiles 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Perkins2012"

\end_inset

.
 For example, the use an arbitrary number consecutive days that a fixed
 temperature value—also arbitrary—is exceeded 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nairn2013,Perkins2012"

\end_inset

.
 However, is difficult to make comparisons among the proposed definitions
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Perkins2012"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, in Adelaide, the declaration of a heatwave requires five consecutiv
e days with maximum temperature exceeding 35 
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

C 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nairn2013"

\end_inset

.
 In the same city, a heatwave is also declared after three consecutive days
 above 40 
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

C.
 Although, maximum temperature is not the only temperature variable used.
 Setting thresholds that include minimum temperature is also common 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Perkins2012,Pezza2011"

\end_inset

.
 This variable accounts for the dissipation of heat at night after a hot
 day.
 Temperature is an important variable of heatwaves as well as of fire weather.
 For this reason, heatwaves are usually linked with increased bushfire risk
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nairn2013,Perkins2012,Pezza2011"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, is important to understand heatwaves behaviour and its relationship
 with fire weather.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Australia, heatwaves occur because of three processes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "McBride2009"

\end_inset

.
 First, the advection of hot and dry air.
 An anticyclone advects air from the north desserts to the forested areas
 in southern Australia.
 Secondly, the subsidence of air that brings atmospheric stability.
 This process produces clear skies that increase solar radiation.
 Finally, the increased insolation generates surface heat fluxes.
 These fluxes heat the air in the mixing layer.
 Fire weather comprises these processes as well.
 Although, its analysis of involves more variables and interactions (subsections
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Fire-weather-in-Victoria"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Victoria-fire"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Climate modes of variability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Large-scale meteorological and oceanographic phenomena drive natural climate
 variability.
 These drivers are known as climate modes of variability.
 For example, El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO), Indian Ocean Dipole (IOD),
 and Southern Annular Mode (SAM) are important climate modes of variability.
 This section describes them since they can exert significant influence
 on fire weather.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
El Niño-Southern Oscillation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO) is a is a large-scale process that drives
 climate on a global scale.
 During ENSO events, the Tropical Pacifc Ocean interacts with the atmosphere
 in a coupled system.
 The most common manifestation of this process is the warming and cooling
 of sea surface temperature.
 Warming conditions represent 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

El Niño
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 conditions.
 This state usually bring above-average precipitation in th coasts of Ecuador
 and Peru 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Aceituno1988"

\end_inset

, while bringing hot and dry conditions in the other side of the Pacific
 Ocean in Indonesia and Australia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Williams1999,Wooster2012"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, cool anomalies in the same region represent 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

La Niña
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 conditions.
 The ENSO phenomena is referred as oscillation since these two phases—warm
 and cool—alternate in periods of approximately four years.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These changing conditions in the sea surface temperature reverse the Walker
 circulation.
 This change in the circulation pattern drives the atmospheric response,
 which can have an effect in places distant where it started.
 This type of response is referred as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

teleconnection
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The change in the atmospheric circulation pattern has a strong linkage
 with the ocean.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The normal state of the Tropical Pacific Ocean is relatively cool waters
 in the east and warm conditions to the west.
 Convection usually takes place in the west, which generates easterly winds
 near to the surface of the ocean.
 The hot and moist air mass originated in the west travel with a westely
 direction in the upper troposphere.
 Along the way it loses heat and moisture.
 Cool and dry air sinks in the east side of the ocean reinforcing the circulatio
n pattern.
 This circulation parttern is known as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Walker
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 circulation, name coined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bjerknes1969"

\end_inset

 in honour to Sir Gilbert Thomas Walker.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A weekening of the easterlies reduces the upwelling in the eastern part
 of the Tropical Pacific Ocean.
 This produces an increase in the sea surface temperature, which transfers
 heat to the atmosphere weakinning the Walker circulation and in extreme
 cases reversing it.
 These changes in sea surface temperature produced by the changes in wind
 stress over the ocean are called an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

El Niño
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 event.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the same time, the changes in the circulation of air masses produced
 by the heat flux—changes in sea surface temperatures—produce variations
 in surface pressures along the Tropcial Pacific.
 This is the main manifestation of a larger phenomena called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Southern Oscillation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 For this reason this phenomena is regarded as coupled ocean-atmophere process.
 The name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

El Niño-Southern Oscillation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 aims to reflect this complexity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common ENSO metric is the Southern Oscillation Index (SOI).
 The SOI represents the difference in normalized surface pressure between
 Taihiti and Darwin, Australia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "NOAA"

\end_inset

.
 I adopted the SOI’s calculation method proposed by the National Oceanic
 and Atmospheric Administration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "NOAA"

\end_inset

.
 The index reflects the changes in air-mass fluxes in the tropical Pacific
 Ocean.
 These fluxes, are a manifestation of changes in sea surface temperature
 (SST).
 The SOI has an open ended scale with positive and negative values.
 A negative SOI value represents above-average warm SST conditions in the
 eastern tropical Pacific Ocean.
 This represents an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

El Niño
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 phase of the phenomenon.
 El Niño brings wet conditions to the coasts of southern Ecuador and northern
 Peru.
 The opposite pattern occurs with a positive SOI value, representing a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

La Niña
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 phase.
\end_layout

