\begin_layout Subsection
Southern Annular Mode
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Southern Annular Mode (SAM) is the main source of interannual climate
 variability in the Southern Hemisphere 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ThompsonandSolomon2002"

\end_inset

.
 This refers to the zonally symetric circulation around Antartica.
 The SAM produces an alternating pattern of strong and weak westerly winds
 in this region.
 This winds are cold and wet and surround Antartica as a belt.
 The SAM drives the expansion and contraction of the circulation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This phenomena is caused by the non-uniform heating of the Earth 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "KingandTurner2007"

\end_inset

.
 This heating regulates heat and mass transport that creates zones of high
 and low pressure in the planet.
 The intensity of the pressure gradient between midlatitudes and latitudes
 close to the South Pole drives the SAM.
 Anomalously high pressures in midlatitudes and low pressures close to the
 poles strenghten the circumpolar vortex.
 The strengthenning process shifts the circulation close to the pole.
 This contraction of the circulation belt produces below-average precipitation
 in many regions of the Southern Hemisphere.
 This process refers to a positive SAM event (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Positive-phase-of-Southern-Annular-Mode"

\end_inset

).
 On the other hand, when the pressure anomalies show the opposite pattern
 the circumpolar vortex is weakened and the circulation is shifted away
 from the South Pole.
 The effect of precipitation over the same regions is the opposite.
 This produces a negative SAM event.
\end_layout

