\begin_layout Standard
Bushfires in Victoria have had a significant impact.
 There is more documentation of bushfire impacts after the European settlement
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 For example, half of the economic loss in Australia occurred in this region
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Luke1978"

\end_inset

.
 Most of these impacts correspond to major catastrophic events 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Blanchi2012"

\end_inset

.
 Three of the most serious catastrophes were “Black Friday”, “Ash Wednesday”,
 and “Black Saturday” 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 To better understand bushfires in Victoria it is convenient to examine
 these major events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The “Black Friday” bushfires occurred on January 13
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 1939 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 In this event, 71 people died and fires burned 1.5 to 2 million hectares
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 This event motivated authorities to create a special commission—Royal Comission
—to investigate its causes deeply.
 A prolonged drought, and a hot and dry summer created the conditions for
 this event to occur.
 Additionally, the causes of the fires were anthropogenic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 This commission fostered laws and institutions that aim to prevent and
 control bushfires 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 Some of the institutions exist even today.
 For example, the former Forests Commission, now Department of Environment,
 Land, Water, and Planning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
“Ash Wednesday” occurred on February 16
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 1983 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 This event generated over 100 fires across the state 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 The fires killed 47 people and burned 210,000 hectares 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 Approximately 82,500 hectares were public land including areas in the Dandenong
 Ranges National Park 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 A 10-month drought preceded these fires 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 On the day of the fires, temperatures reached 40 
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

C, and relative humidity was below 15%.
 Hot and dry northerly winds created these conditions.
 Additionally, a strong cold front increased the difficulty to suppress
 the fires 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 This cold front changed the direction of the fire front and increased its
 size.
 The causes of the fires were accidental, deliberate and some not identified
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last catastrophic event was the worst in Australian history.
 “Black Saturday” occurred on February 7th, 2009 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VBRC_2009_final_report"

\end_inset

.
 These fires killed 173 people 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VBRC_2009_final_report"

\end_inset

 and destroyed 430,000 hectares 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DEPIa"

\end_inset

.
 A prolonged heatwave preceded the event 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VBRC_2009_final_report"

\end_inset

.
 This heatwave produced three consecutive days with temperature above 43
 
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

C.
 Melbourne—capital of Victoria— reached this temperature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VBRC_2009_final_report"

\end_inset

.
 Other areas in Victoria experienced record-breaking temperatures reaching
 46 
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

C on “Black Saturday” 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VBRC_2009_final_report"

\end_inset

.
 These fires motivated the conformation of another commission—2009 Victorian
 Bushfires Royal Comission—.
 The commission clearly identified the characteristics of the fires.
 The main features included: rapid spread, fires crowned in forested areas,
 convection columns, extensive spotting, and a cold front that changed the
 direction of the fires and their extension 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VBRC_2009_final_report"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Fire-columns-during-Black-Saturday"

\end_inset

 illustrates the intensity of the fires.
 The commission estimated the economic losses of these fires to reach $4
 billion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VBRC_2009_final_report"

\end_inset

.
